      {
        "id": "sec_4",
        "document_id": "95b06e93627aab6fcdfb83214bda2acd",
        "title": "3.1  Defining the benchmark tax system",
        "level": 1,
        "page_start": 9,
        "page_end": 12,
        "child_sections": [],
        "key_entities": [],
        "summary": "The section outlines the process of defining a benchmark tax system, which serves as a reference point for identifying tax expenditures—deviations from standard tax rates. It emphasizes the importance of judgment in establishing this benchmark, particularly in relation to positive import tax expenditures, where importers benefit from lower customs duties than the benchmark rates. The report also clarifies that certain exemptions, such as those for diplomats and international agreements, are included in the benchmark, while higher applied tax rates are considered part of the benchmark to avoid negative tax expenditures.",
        "data_types_present": [
          "paragraphs"
        ],
