      {
        "id": "sec_5",
        "document_id": "95b06e93627aab6fcdfb83214bda2acd",
        "title": "3.2  Estimating tax expenditures",
        "level": 1,
        "page_start": 13,
        "page_end": 14,
        "child_sections": [],
        "key_entities": [],
        "summary": "Section 3.2 discusses the estimation of tax expenditures in Ethiopia's import tax system, emphasizing that the overall tax expenditure is the difference between the benchmark tax and the actual tax collected. It highlights the complexity of the sequential nature of customs duty, excise tax, VAT, and surtax, where earlier tax reductions can affect the tax base for subsequent taxes, potentially leading to misleading comparisons. The section also outlines how indirect effects of tax expenditures are accounted for in the main estimates, specifically focusing on customs duty tax expenditures resulting from exemptions and reduced rates.",
        "data_types_present": [
          "paragraphs"
        ],
