      {
        "id": "sec_13",
        "document_id": "95b06e93627aab6fcdfb83214bda2acd",
        "title": "5.  Conclusions and recommendations",
        "level": 1,
        "page_start": 41,
        "page_end": 43,
        "child_sections": [],
        "key_entities": [],
        "summary": "The report analyzes import tax expenditures incurred by the Ethiopian government from FY 2018/19 to FY 2020/21, revealing a significant increase in these expenditures, which reached ETB 120.7 billion in FY 2020/21, constituting 21.3% of import value and 2.8% of GDP. It emphasizes the need for ongoing scrutiny of these expenditures, particularly in high-impact categories like motor vehicles and animal fats, while recommending that tax expenditure reporting be expanded to include domestic taxes to better understand their overall impact on revenue. The findings highlight the importance of evaluating whether these costly tax expenditures effectively achieve their intended objectives amidst declining tax-to-GDP ratios.",
        "data_types_present": [
          "lists",
          "paragraphs"
        ],
